Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Process Designer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-7)

The editor is the central part of the Process Designer workbench. There is an editor tab for each open file. The tab header displays the file name. Infinica Process Definition (IPD) files are opened in a graphical editor containing the process diagram. In addition to this main type of editor, Process Designer also includes an editor type for XML files and an editor type for arbitrary text files. Those are only support tools which are not required for the main tasks of Process Designer and are therefore not described in detail.

For an IPD file, the active editor tab contains the design page which is the main interface for creating and editing process components. It consists of an editing area displaying the graphical representation of a process on the left side and a palette, listing all the available components on the right side. On the bottom of the editor there is a *Code* tab which can be used to switch to a text editor which displays the XML representation of the process, as it is persisted in the IPD file. This view exists for display purposes only, it is not possible to modify the process.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 2. Empty Editor*

This section describes the functionality of the editor in the standard mode. The differences in behaviour of the data mode are described in section [Data Mode](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode).

## Palette
The palette contains two types of entries: tools and elements. Tools can be activated via mouse click. They change the behaviour of the mouse cursor in the editor. Elements can be added to the diagram either by activating the entry and clicking in the editing area or by dragging the entry into the editing area. The elements include all process elements which can be part of the process. Each palette category contains either tools or elements.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 3. Palette*

The palette can be hidden by clicking on the arrow button on the right side of the header. Change the size by dragging the border to the editing area or clicking *Resize* in the context menu of the header. It can be moved to the left or right side of the editing area by drag and dropping the palette header or via the context menu of the palette header. The palette can be customized using the *Settings* entry in the context menu of the palette body.

### Selection Tools
The *Select* tool represents the default mouse behaviour in the editing area. When active, a mouse click selects process components. Activating the *Marquee* tool lets you draw a selection box which selects everything which is completely enclosed by the box. The same can also be done with the *Select* entry.

### Note
This category only contains the *Note* element. Use it to add notes to the process diagram. For more information on notes see [Notes and Note Connections](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-editor#datamode) in [Special Elements](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-editor#special-elements).

### Elements
Contains all the standard process elements which are fixed parts of the Process Engine functionality. Activate an entry and click on the editing area to add it to the process.

### Connections
Contains tools for connections. Create a connection by activating the tool and clicking first on the source, then on the target element. For the *Note Connection* entry either source or target need to be a note.

### Tasks
Contains all task types which are available for the currently selected Process Engine. This Process Engine and with it the available tasks can be changed by selecting a different Engine configuration in the combo box of the toolbar. The specified engine must be running and reachable to retrieve the tasks, otherwise the palette category is empty. Activate an entry and click on the editing area to add a task element with the selected type to the process.

### Activity Modules
This category contains subcategories which represent the available activity modules of the currently selected Process Engine. This Process Engine and with it the available activity modules can be changed by selecting a different Engine configuration in the combo box of the toolbar. The specified engine must be running and reachable to retrieve the modules, otherwise the palette category is empty. The subcategories contain elements for all activities of that module. Create an activity by activating the entry and clicking on the editing area.

## Editing Area
In the editing area, the process diagram is displayed. The basic process structure can be modified here. It is resized automatically to fit all elements. Use the combo box with the percentage values in the toolbar to set a zoom for the editing area. The grid in the editing area can be hidden using the *Toggle Grid* menu entry in the *Layout* category.

### Process Elements
Process elements can be added via the palette, as described above. Elements which are displayed as rectangles (mapping element, activity, group, task, script, process include) have a header, which displays the elements icon on the left side and the element type in the middle. Directly below the header is a label, which is either the name of the element if a name is set, or otherwise the id. Elements which have a different form (start element, end element, wait element, decision) only display the label (name or id). A unique id is generated automatically for each element which is created. If the user provides a name for the element, the name is used to derive the id, otherwise the id derives from the type. When hovering over an element, a button pad appears beyond the upper right corner, providing fast access to some of the actions described in the subsection Actions. Process components can be deleted using the *delete* entry in the menu, toolbar and button pad. Process elements can be moved via drag and drop. Resizing elements works by selecting the element and dragging one of the points of the selection border to the preferred size.

An open process is constantly validated. If this validation mechanism finds problems in the process, which might lead to errors during execution, they are displayed in the *Validation *view and if they are assignable to a specific element, a warning or error icon is shown in the upper right corner of the element. Hovering over this icon will show a message describing the problem. Each type of process element has one or two colours assigned. These colours can be changed in the *Preferences* dialog under style.

### Connections
Connections between elements can be created in two ways: Either using the palette entry as described above or by dragging the *Create Connection* button from the button pad onto the target element and selecting the connection type from the appearing pop-up menu. Most process elements can have an arbitrary number of incoming and a single outgoing connection. Decisions can also have an arbitrary number of outgoing connections. Start elements cannot have incoming connections and end elements cannot have outgoing connections.

Target and source of a connection can be changed by selecting the connection and dragging the point where it is connected with an element, onto a different element. If a process element is dropped onto a connection (either a new element taken from the palette or an existing element moved from a different location), the connection target is set to the dropped element and a new connection from the dropped element to the previous target is created. If a start or end element is dropped, no new connection is created. In case of a start element the existing connections source is changed to the start element, instead of the target. If source or target of a connection are deleted, the connection will also be deleted.

The end of a connection is always oriented towards the center of the process element it connects to and will move automatically if the process element is moved or resized. Connections can be shaped using bend points. When selecting a connection, a bend point appears in the middle of the connection line. Add a bend by dragging the bend point to the intended position. Each time a new bend is added, a new bend point appears on both sides of the bend. Remove a bend by dragging the bend point back into a straight line. When moving a single process element bend points keep their position, when moving both ends of a connection simultaneously, bend points are also moved accordingly.

### Special Elements
#### Decisions
Decisions are the only process elements which can have multiple outgoing connections. For each connection originating from a decision the decision maintains a condition which determines if this connection should be taken. Conditions are added and removed simply by adding and removing outgoing connections of the decision. The conditions can be modified via the *Properties* view in the *Main* tab, either by selecting the decision and selecting the condition in the table or by directly selecting the outgoing connection in the editor and entering the condition in the *Condition* text field.

#### Groups
Group elements can contain other process components. Managing process components within a group works the same as with components on the root level. Activate an element in the palette and click in the body of the group to add it. Existing elements can also be added to the group by simply moving it into the body. Elements within a group can be connected among each other, but not with elements outside of their group. A group can again contain other groups.

Groups can be collapsed. Collapsing sets the elements size to the default for regular process elements and hides the elements contained in the group. Expanding reverts it to the normal view. Collapsing/expanding elements can trigger a *Layout Process* action if it is configured to do so in the preferences in the section *Automatic Layout Configuration*.

#### Include Process
The path to the process referenced by an include process element is set in the *Main* tab of the *Properties* view. This process can be opened in a separate editor using the *Open Process *entry in the context menu of the element. The process can also be loaded directly into the containing process using the *Include Process* entry in the context menu. A referenced process which is included in the parent process cannot be modified. Modifications done within an include process element will not be saved.

> Note

The path to the referenced process is resolved relative to the containing process. To open or include a process in the Designer, the containing process must be saved to a file.

#### Notes and Note Connections
Notes and Note Connections are not part of the process model defined by the Process Engine. They are graphical helper elements and have no impact on process execution. Their main purpose is the documenting the process. A note is a container for any text a user wants to provide as part of the process diagram. Note connections are an optional addition to a note, which link the note to a process elements. The text of a note can be edited via the *Properties* view in the *Note* tab, while the note is selected in the editor. Notes and note connections can be completely hidden/shown using the *Show Notes* menu entry.

## Actions
Below is a list and description of actions available in the editor. There are different ways of triggering these actions, including menu entries, toolbar entries, the editor context menu, the button pad or shortcuts. Note that some of these actions might not be available or show a different behaviour if the focus is not on the editor.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) *Undo* (context menu, menu, toolbar): Reverts the last change.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) *Redo* (context menu, menu, toolbar): Applies the last undone change again.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) *Cut* (context menu, menu, toolbar): Cuts the selected process element(s) from the process and puts them to the clipboard.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABhSURBVDhPY2TAARwcHP5DmeQBkAGEAEgNE1Q92YCRWKfu378fykIAR0dH4p2KDVDFC6MGDAYDwAkJWyJBBuAEgwsQm5BsbGzsoVpQAHW8AGXjBX/+/HE4cuTIQSgXChgYAJ59lAwOxsZyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) *Copy* (context menu, menu, toolbar): Puts the selected process element(s) to the clipboard.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) *Paste* (context menu, menu, toolbar): Pastes process element(s) from the clipboard to the process.

- *Select All* (menu): Selects all process elements in the editor.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,) *Delete* (context menu, button pad, menu, toolbar): Deletes the selected process component(s).

- ![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) / ![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) *Collapse/Expand* (context menu, button pad): This is only available for group elements. Collapsing sets the elements size to the default for regular process elements and hides the elements contained in the group. Expanding reverts it to the normal view.

- *Layout Process* (context menu, menu): Automatically creates a layout for the process and applies it. Any previous layout information is overwritten.

-  ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABESURBVDhPYxgFlANGKM3g4ODwH8oEgwMHDsDlQACXPJgASSJrQFcMA+hq4HxkDTA2sWIUuwCnJmTFIEBIfhQMHGBgAACMnjJ/NFDwMwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==) *Create Connection* (button pad): Drag and drop this button on a process element to create a connection.

- *Open Process* (context menu): Open the referenced process of an include process element in a separate editor.

- ![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) / ![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) *Include Process*/*Close Process* (context menu): Include loads the referenced process of an include process element into the containing process. When a process is already included, it can be removed via close.
